{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3666fd63-26d5-46ff-ae92-0093a3021443","content":"CLR activation logs diagnose **runtime loading issues** (wrong CLR version, missing runtime, etc.) — they won't help with a `NullReferenceException`, which is a code-level bug (accessing a null object reference).\n\nLet me check if you have any relevant files here to work with:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_015eJHj6NdZkpVwezXWZqMjf","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Exploring working directory"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01DMkNxy3vWz9nhiLEq191so","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-ef52a0d1b5ff4387ae72246c54fa10c6"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-ef52a0d1b5ff4387ae72246c54fa10c6."}],"interactionId":"9c1e3779-f805-4027-b9c0-2d1772748d37","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException. However, there are a few things to note:\n\n1. They mention \"CLR activation logs\" - there's a skill available called `clr-activation-debugging` that is specifically designed for diagnosing .NET Framework CLR activation issues.\n\n2. However, a NullReferenceException is typically a code-level bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with which runtime version gets loaded, not application-level exceptions.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The user says the app crashes with a NullReferenceException after startup, and they want me to analyze CLR activation logs. \n\nCLR activation logs are really about runtime loading and binding, not about NullReferenceExceptions themselves. But since the user specifically asked about CLR activation logs and there's a skill for that, I should probably check if they have any relevant files first and clarify that while CLR activation logs might show runtime loading issues, a NullReferenceException is typically a code-level problem that would need different diagnostics.","outputTok